## Key Considerations

### Why Multivariate Over Univariate?

A standard RPE table only uses **(reps, RPE)** as inputs. Multivariate regression lets you account for:

1. **Set order / fatigue** — your RPE 8 on set 4 corresponds to a different %1RM than RPE 8 on set 1
2. **Exercise specificity** — your bench RPE curve may differ from your squat RPE curve
3. **Time/recovery** — morning vs. evening sessions, days since last training

### Data Quality Caveats

> [!WARNING]
> - Your RPE data only includes integer values (6-10), no half-steps (6.5, 7.5, etc.)
> - RPE is self-reported and subjective — consistency over time matters
> - ~30% of data is RPE 8, which may bias the model
> - Some exercises have very few RPE data points (< 10 sets)

### Exercise-Specific Models

For your big 3 lifts (bench/squat/deadlift), you have enough data to fit **per-exercise models** which would be more accurate than a single global model:

| Lift | Sets with RPE | Enough for regression? |
|------|:-:|:-:|
| Bench Press (Barbell) | 140 | ✅ Yes |
| Squat (Barbell) | 121 | ✅ Yes |
| Deadlift (Barbell) | 82 | ✅ Yes |
| Triceps Extension | 105 | ✅ Yes |
| Back Extension | 101 | ✅ Yes |
| Chest Fly | 82 | ✅ Yes |
| Lying Leg Curl | 77 | ✅ Yes |
| Incline DB Bench | 73 | ✅ Yes |
| Most accessories | < 50 | ⚠️ Use global model |

